  "prompt": "What do Israelis think of Jesus?",
  "response": "In Israel, attitudes toward Jesus are diverse and influenced by a variety of cultural, religious, and historical factors. Judaism, the predominant religion, does not recognize Jesus as the Messiah or as divine, so most Jewish Israelis do not view Jesus in the same way as Christians do. However, perceptions vary:\n\n1. **Secular Israelis**: Many secular Israelis may view Jesus as a historical figure or a significant religious leader in Christianity, but not as someone of personal religious importance.\n\n2. **Religious Jews**: Orthodox and ultra-Orthodox Jews generally reject the idea of Jesus as the Messiah and do not regard him as a religious figure within Judaism. Some individuals within the Haredi community might even view him negatively due to historical tensions between Judaism and Christianity.\n\n3. **Arab Christians**: Israel has a minority of Arab Christians, who make up about 2% of the population. For them, Jesus is central to their faith as the Son of God and Savior, in line with Christian beliefs.\n\n4. **Academic/Humanitarian Perspectives**: Some Israelis, particularly academics or those interested in interfaith dialogue, may appreciate Jesus as a moral teacher or a figure who promoted values like compassion and justice.\n\nOverall, while Jesus is not a focus of Jewish religious practice, Israelis' views on him depend on their individual backgrounds, beliefs, and cultural contexts. Interfaith efforts and dialogue sometimes foster mutual understanding between Jews and Christians regarding Jesus and his role in history.",
